Yes, absolutely! ✅ You can add **normal plain strings** (not HTML) to the file content — **but it depends on the file format you're generating**.

---

### ⚠️ If you're generating a `.doc` (Word-compatible) file:

Word expects **HTML**, so strings should be inside tags like `<p>`, `<h1>`, etc.

But you **can still insert normal strings** — just wrap them in `<p>` or convert them to HTML first.

---

### ✅ Example: Add Plain Strings to Word `.doc` Blob

```ts
const extraText = `
Summary of the Report:
Generated using internal tool for LLM formatting.

Please verify totals and attribution tags manually before sending to analysts.
`;

const htmlifiedExtraText = extraText
  .split('\n')
  .map(line => `<p>${line}</p>`)
  .join('');

// Combine with HTML prompt content
const htmlContent = marked.parse(this.prompt) as string;

const wordHtml = `
  <html xmlns:o='urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office' 
        xmlns:w='urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:word' 
        xmlns='http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40'>
  <head><meta charset='utf-8'></head>
  <body>
    ${htmlifiedExtraText}
    <hr/>
    ${htmlContent}
  </body>
  </html>
`;

const blob = new Blob([wordHtml], {
  type: 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document',
});
```

---

### ✅ TL;DR

* ✅ Yes, you can use **normal strings**
* ✅ Just wrap each line in `<p>line</p>` to make Word understand them
* ❌ Don’t use raw plain text in `.doc` blobs — it won’t render properly in Word

---

Let me know if you want to support both **Markdown** and **plain text (.txt)** downloads side by side!
